            "creation_date": 1420095302,
            "body": "<p>It is easy with intellij idea 14:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>just put cursor on the string concatenation<\/li>\n<li>Press <kbd>alt<\/kbd> + <kbd>enter<\/kbd><\/li>\n<li>Select \"Copy String concatenation text into clipboard\"<\/li>\n<li>Paste result somewhere.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n",
            "answer_id": 27728900,
            "question_id": 15335260,
            "last_edit_date": 1469103595
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6d8ebb117e8d83d74ea95fbdd0f87e13?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 11683,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 22656,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/22656/jon-skeet",
                "reputation": 1521060,
                "display_name": "Jon Skeet",
                "accept_rate": 86
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1362994907,
            "creation_date": 1362994907,
            "body": "<p>You would be able to see the compile-time concatenated string <code>\"ONETWOTHREE\"<\/code> by decompiling the bytecode:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>javap -c StringHolder\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>and looking at the first assignment.<\/p>\n\n<p>The concatenation for <code>first + second + third<\/code> will still be done at execution time rather than compile-time, so I'd expect to see code using <code>StringBuilder<\/code> or <code>StringBuffer<\/code>, and there'll be no \"result\" of that string concatenation without running the code.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15335312,
            "question_id": 15335260
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c1be932bbc82f9808ccd623e58a7a4a1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1903805,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1719067,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1719067/narendra-pathai",
                "reputation": 42065,
                "display_name": "Narendra Pathai",
                "accept_rate": 73
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": -1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1362995054,
            "creation_date": 1362995054,
            "body": "<pre><code>public static final String ONE = \"ONE\";\npublic static final String TWO = \"TWO\";\npublic static final String THREE = \"THREE\";\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>are <strong>compile time constants<\/strong> and will be inlined during compile time.<\/p>\n\n<p>So you can see the result in the <code>.class<\/code> file generated by decompiling. The other one <code>result<\/code> will not be visible until runtime.<\/p>\n\n<p>For <code>someVariable<\/code> you will see something like <code>someVariable = \"ONETWOTHREE\";<\/code> in the decompiled code. The compiler does this for optimization so is visible. <\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 15335365,
            "question_id": 15335260
        }
